Objectives

getting counts for different groups use lubridate to parse dates find confidence intervervals and do t tests heatmap with geom_title()

#Import lobster data

lobster_abundance <- read_csv(here::here("data","lobster_abundance.csv"), 
                              na = "-99999") %>% 
  clean_names()
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   DATE = col_character(),
##   SITE = col_character(),
##   TRANSECT = col_double(),
##   REPLICATE = col_character(),
##   SIZE_MM = col_double(),
##   LOBSTER_COUNT = col_double()
## )

Use tidyr::uncount() funtion to expand a frequency distribution

lobster_tidy <- lobster_abundance %>% 
  tidyr::uncount(lobster_count)

Now each lobster has its own row, this is tidy format.

Lets look at this in multiple ways:

ggplot(data =  lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_jitter(aes(color=site), 
              width = 0.2, 
              alpha = 0.3)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data =  lobster_tidy, aes(x = site, y = size_mm)) +
  geom_violin(aes(color=site), 
              alpha = 0.3)
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_ydensity).

ggplot(data =  lobster_tidy, aes(x = size_mm)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = site)) +
  facet_wrap(~site, scales = "free")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

ggplot(data =  lobster_tidy, aes(sample = size_mm)) +
  geom_qq(size = 0.5) + 
  facet_wrap(~site, scales = "free")
## Warning: Removed 6 rows containing non-finite values (stat_qq).

Use ‘lubridate’ to parse dates and times: Add a new column with ‘mutate()’ that contains my date as an actual date

lobster_date <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  mutate(
    date_new = lubridate::mdy(date)
  )

Parse ‘Date’ column to get the different peices (month, year) seperated

lobster_parse_date <- lobster_date %>%
  mutate(
    obs_month = lubridate::month(date_new, label = TRUE) , 
    obs_year = lubridate::year(date_new)
  )

Count lobsters by different groupings. I want to count the number of lobsters by year and month

lobster_ym <- lobster_parse_date %>% 
  count(obs_year, obs_month)

#group_by + summarize + n()
lobster_summary <- lobster_parse_date %>%
  group_by(site) %>% 
  summarize(
    mean_size = mean(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE), 
    sd_size = sd(size_mm, na.rm = TRUE), 
    sample_n = n()
    
  )

Confidence intervals and t-tests:

Use the ‘t.test()’ funtion to find confidence intervals and perform t tests

ivee_lobsters <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "IVEE") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

t.test(ivee_lobsters)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  ivee_lobsters
## t = 245.23, df = 2302, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  72.99130 74.16806
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##  73.57968

two-sample t-test: Is there a significant difference in mean lobster lengths b/w naples and mohawk

napl_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "NAPL") %>%
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site == "MOHK") %>% 
  pull(size_mm)

mohk_napl_ttest <- t.test(napl_sample, mohk_sample)
mohk_napl_ttest
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  napl_sample and mohk_sample
## t = 19.849, df = 1850.8, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  10.19806 12.43436
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  78.18454  66.86833

Mean lobster size differed significantly b/w mohawk and naples reefs (t(1850.7720862) = 19.849)

maybe an easier way…

lobster_2sample <- lobster_tidy %>% 
  filter(site %in% c("NAPL", "MOHK"))

ttest_2 <- t.test(size_mm ~ site, data = lobster_2sample)

make a geom_tile heatmap

ggplot(data = lobster_ysite, aes(x = obs_year, y = site)) +
  geom_tile(aes(fill = n))
